                <section id="nicolas_cage" class="mm-parallax-window" data-sizes="[[300,158],[320,168],[350,184],[400,210],[450,237],[500,263],[550,289],[600,316],[640,337],[650,342],[700,368],[750,394],[768,404],[800,421],[850,447],[900,473],[950,500],[1000,526],[1024,539],[1100,579],[1200,631],[1300,684],[1400,736],[1500,789],[1600,841],[1700,894],[1800,947],[1900,999],[2000,1052],[2100,1104],[2200,1157],[2300,1210],[2400,1262],[2500,1315],[2600,1367],[2700,1420]]" data-path="http://www.gq.com/static/long-form/images/0.7.23/pages/nicolas_cage/opener/">
                    <div></div>
                </section>
                <div class="dotted-line"></div>
                <div id="title-card" style="background-color:#fff200">
                    <div><span>GQ <span>Longform</span></span>
                        <h1>The 111 Reasons Why Nicolas Cage Is a National Treasure</h1>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div id="meta">
                    <div>
                        <h2>He is one of our greatest actors, just as often one of our worst—and sometimes he's both at the same time. He's an Oscar winner who routinely shows up in straight-to-video dreck, a global superstar who got so rich and so famous he bought castles (plural), cobras (plural again), and at least one island—then got in so much tax trouble he had to sell it all. He speaks in a wonderfully bizarre mix of Zen koans and comic-book argot, and he's back this month with <em>Left Behind</em>, a Rapture-themed Christian dispensationalist airline thriller (!). But—we love him. Oh, how we love him.</h2>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </header>
            <section class="copy" data-chapter-top="0" data-chapter-bottom="0">
                <div>
                    <header>
                        <h3>Because Really, the Best Hollywood Actors Are Nuts</h3>
                    </header>
                    <p><span>No less than rock 'n' roll,</span> movies have always been a wonderful and even lucrative asylum for seriously warped eccentrics&mdash;sometimes behind the camera, but just as often in front of it. With Marlon Brando long gone, swapping garbled anecdotes in the great beyond with Errol Flynn, what makes Nicolas Cage the new king of this particular hill is that no one doubts he's a lunatic.</p>
                    <p>Okay, with the conceivable exception of Cage himself. Yet who'd rely on <i>his</i> opinion, besides a fellow straitjacket supermodel? He can't act without acting out, and just like the Sex Pistols, he means it, man. But what he means when he means it, man, is a riddle only tomorrow's Martian archaeologists stand a chance of unraveling.</p>
                    <aside class="mm-sidebar">
                        <section class="mm-related-stories">
                            <h5>Related Content</h5><span></span>
                            <ul>
                                <li>
                                    <a href="http://www.gq.com/women/201410/lauren-cohan-walking-dead-photos"><img src="http://www.gq.com/static/long-form/images/0.7.23/pages/nicolas_cage/related/1.jpg" width="96" height="96" alt="Meet The Walking Dead’s (Sorta-) Southern Belle, Lauren Cohan">
                                        <h6>Meet The Walking Dead’s (Sorta-) Southern Belle, Lauren Cohan</h6>
                                    </a>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <a href="http://www.gq.com/food-travel/201409/the-50-best-craft-beers-as-chosen-by-experts"><img src="http://www.gq.com/static/long-form/images/0.7.23/pages/nicolas_cage/related/2.jpg" width="96" height="96" alt="The 50 Best Craft Beers Every Man Must Try">
                                        <h6>The 50 Best Craft Beers Every Man Must Try</h6>
                                    </a>
                                </li>
                            </ul>
                        </section>
                    </aside>
                    <p>A buttload of mostly severely IQ-challenged movies removed from Cage's all but forgotten Oscar win for 1995's <i>Leaving Las Vegas,</i> his unrepentant nuttiness makes him&mdash;no other word&mdash;precious. Tom Cruise may be almost as loco, but he's been a careful CEO with his own career, which ain't something you can say about our Nic from <i>Vampire's Kiss</i> onward. Yet his only try at making like a conventionally romantic movie star, in the dreary <i>Captain Corelli's Mandolin,</i> was the only time he's been dull. Even though he wouldn't have lasted this long if he didn't have talent to burn, bringing the freaky is what we count on him for.</p>
                    <div class="mm-inset">
                        <div>
                            <div class="img-container"><img src="http://www.gq.com/static/long-form/images/0.7.23/pages/nicolas_cage/inset/1.jpg" alt="The Cage-bombed nutso pantheon: clockwise from top left, Errol Flynn, Charlie Chaplin, Marlon Brando, and Johnny Depp." height="826" width="575"> <span class="black"><p><i class="illustrator"></i> Steve Brodner</p></span>
                            </div>
                            <div class="caption">
                                <p>The Cage-bombed nutso pantheon: clockwise from top left, Errol Flynn, Charlie Chaplin, Marlon Brando, and Johnny Depp.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    <p>We may not know why we need Nicolas Cage, but plainly we do. This hyperactive one-man train wreck is the dude we'd all want to spend our last twenty-four hours being before a nuclear war, because retaining dignity sure won't be much of an issue <i>then.</i> And if you think those Martians won't find Cage a million times more interesting than Tom Cruise when they're parsing twenty-first-century life on our little asteroid, guess again. —<em>Tom Carson</em>
                    </p>
                </div>
            </section>
            <div id="timeline" class="photo-scrollr">
                <div class="swipe"></div>
                <div class="touchscroller" data-id="timeline" data-width="5629" data-height="571" alt="Because He Can’t Help Making Great Movies—and Horrible Movies—Often at the Same Time" style="margin-bottom: 40px"><img src="http://www.gq.com/static/long-form/images/0.7.23/pages/nicolas_cage/photo_scrollr/1.jpg">
                </div><span class="left"></span> <span class="right"></span>
            </div>
            <section class="copy" data-chapter-top="1" data-chapter-bottom="1">
                <div>
                    <header>
                        <h3>Because the Internet Will Never Stop Doing Funny Things with Him</h3>
                    </header>
                    <p>As long as he keeps losing his shit on-camera and plotting to steal the Declaration of Independence, Nicolas Cage will be the gift that keeps on giving to the Internet. (Behold the madness that is Reddit’s <a href="http://www.reddit.com/r/onetruegod">r/OneTrueGod</a> subreddit.) Five ways he's been meme-canonized online. —<em>Freddie Campion</em>
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div class="multimedia-list">
                    <div class="listItem">
                        <div class="img"><img src="http://www.gq.com/static/long-form/images/0.7.23/pages/nicolas_cage/multimedia_list/1.gif" alt="Scenes from The Wicker Man" height="" width="">
                        </div>
                        <div class="text">
                            <p><span>Scenes from The Wicker Man</span> Invoked completely at random, the film—with famously insane lines like, simply “THE BEES!”—feels like it was written just so the Internet could make fun of it.</p>
                            <p></p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="listItem">
                        <div class="img"><img src="http://www.gq.com/static/long-form/images/0.7.23/pages/nicolas_cage/multimedia_list/2.jpg" alt="“My Hair Is a Bird. Your Argument is Invalid.”" height="" width="">
                        </div>
                        <div class="text">
                            <p><span>“My Hair Is a Bird. Your Argument is Invalid.”</span> If you don&#x27;t get it, that&#x27;s the point. Send to someone you’re deadlocked in argument with. The sheer WTF-ness will immobilize them.</p>
                            <p></p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="listItem">
                        <div class="img"><img src="http://www.gq.com/static/long-form/images/0.7.23/pages/nicolas_cage/multimedia_list/3.gif" alt="“You Don’t Say”" height="" width="">
                        </div>
                        <div class="text">
                            <p><span>“You Don’t Say”</span> It can be hard to convey sarcasm through typing. Luckily, this meme-ified still of Nicolas Cage giving his standard 110 percent in Vampire’s Kiss does it for you!</p>
                            <p></p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="listItem">
                        <div class="img"><img src="http://www.gq.com/static/long-form/images/0.7.23/pages/nicolas_cage/multimedia_list/4.gif" alt="Caging (or Cage-Bombing)" height="" width="">
                        </div>
                        <div class="text">
                            <p><span>Caging (or Cage-Bombing)</span> The art of printing out pictures of his face and placing them in weird and unexpected places.</p>
                            <p></p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </section>
            <section class="copy" data-chapter-top="2" data-chapter-bottom="2">
                <div>
                    <header>
                        <h3></h3>
                    </header>
                    <p><span class="header-span">Nicolas Cage as Everyone</span>The best example of the web's obsession with Nicolas Cage: Turn everyone into Nicolas Cage.</p>
                </div>
            </section>
